[[File:Rev._John_Davies,_Nercwys_NLW3365243.jpg|200px|thumb|John Davies of Nercwys]] '''John Davies''' (John Davies of Nercwys) (born at Llanerch, in the parish of Llanarmon yn Ial 26 May, 1799 and baptised in the Parish Church on 31 May, 1799 the family moved to Rhos Ithel, Nercwys in about 1800 where he died on 5 March 1879) was a Welsh Calvinistic Methodist minister, preacher and writer. His parents were Joseph and Eleanor Davies Nee Parry. Although an itinerant preacher his home remained in [[Nercwys]] area of [[Flintshire]], hence the place name was used as an additional epithet to differentiate him from others named John Davies. He grew up living in the [[Mold]] area. At the age of 16, in 1815, he is known to have become a member of [[Mold]] Methodist Society. A few years later he began preaching, and in 1834 was ordained.
His writings include a commentary on the [[Book of Proverbs]] (1869).
He died in March 1879. <ref>{{cite web|title=John Davies|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-JOH-1799.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|last=Williams|first=Griffith John|accessdate= 13 June 2017}}</ref> His portrait hangs in [[Flintshire]] Record Office along with that of novelist [[Daniel Owen]], who was christened by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://artuk.org/visit/venues/flintshire-record-office-6875|title=Flintshire Record Office|website=Art UK|access-date=25 June 2017}}</ref>
