{{france-artist-stub}}

{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox writer | name = Phyllis Seckler | image = Phyllis Seckler.jpg | pseudonym = Soror Meral | birth_name = Phyllis Evalina Pratt | birth_date = {{Birth date|1917|6|18}} | birth_place = [[Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada | death_date = {{death date and age|2004|5|31|1917|6|18}} | death_place = [[Oroville, California]], United States<ref name=obit>{{cite web | url = http://sorormeral.org/ | title = Religious Leader, Educator Phyllis Seckler Dies at 86 | accessdate = 2011-02-01 | author = College of Thelema | date = 4 June 2004}}</ref> | nationality = American | citizenship = United States | period = 1979–2004 | genre = [[Occult]] studies | subject = Biography, [[astrology]], [[Magick (Thelema)|magick]] | spouse = [[Grady McMurtry]] | influences = [[Thelema]]; [[Aleister Crowley]], [[Jane Wolfe]] }} '''Phyllis Evalina Seckler''' (1917–2004), also known as '''Soror Meral''', was a ninth degree (IX°) member of the "Sovereign Sanctuary of the Gnosis" of [[Ordo Templi Orientis]] (O.T.O.), and a student of [[Jane Wolfe]], herself a student of [[Aleister Crowley]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Starr | first = Martin P. | title = The Unknown God: W. T. Smith and the Thelemites| year = 2003 | publisher = Teitan Press |location = Bolingbrook, Illinois |isbn = 0-933429-07-X |ref=Starr }}</ref>
==Life and career== Under her pen name '''Soror Meral''', Seckler was Master of 418 Lodge of O.T.O. in California from its inception in 1979 until her death.<ref name="Thelemapedia.org">{{cite web|title=Thelemapedia: Phyllis Seckler |url=http://www.thelemapedia.org/index.php/Phyllis_Seckler|website=Thelemapedia.org |accessdate=2011-02-01|date=11 February 2017}}</ref> She was also founder of the College of Thelema; and co-founder (with Anna-Kria King and James A. Eshelman) of the Temple of Thelema, both of which organizations she also led until her death. Prior to her death, she also warranted the founding of the International College of Thelema (formerly known as the College of Thelema of Northern California) as an autonomous continuation of her work, as well as the Temple of the Silver Star (the initiatory Order within the International College of Thelema.) She was a writer for and editor of ''In the Continuum'', the journal of the College of Thelema, for nearly 25 years.<ref name=obit/>
For a brief period in the 1970s, she was married to [[Grady McMurtry]]. It was as a result of a 1968 letter from Seckler that McMurtry (Frater Hymenaeus Alpha) invoked his "emergency powers" to reconstitute Ordo Templi Orientis, which had flagged following the death of [[Aleister Crowley|Aleister Crowley's]] successor as Outer Head of the Order, [[Karl Germer]]. It was under their combined leadership that O.T.O. was incorporated under [[California]] law and began to grow in North America for the first time since Crowley's death.<ref>{{cite book | last = Crowley | first = Aleister| authorlink = Aleister Crowley | editor = Hymenaeus Beta | others = Soror Meral, Research Ed. | title = The Review of Scientific Illuminism: The Official Organ of the O.T.O | edition = Revised | series = The Equinox #10 | volume = III | origyear = March 1986 |date=July 1990 | publisher = [[Weiser Books]] | location = York Beach, Maine | isbn=0-87728-719-8 | ref=Eq310 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>
==Publications== *{{cite book | last = Seckler |editor1=Jerry Cornelius |editor2=Marlene Cornelius | title = Jane Wolfe: Her Life With Aleister Crowley (Part 1) | year = 2003 | publisher = Red Flame #10 | isbn = 0-9712376-2-X }} *{{cite book | last = Seckler |editor1=Jerry Cornelius |editor2=Marlene Cornelius | title = Jane Wolfe: Her Life With Aleister Crowley (Part 2) | year = 2003 | publisher = Red Flame #11 | isbn = 0-9712376-3-8 }} *{{cite book | last = Seckler |editor1=Rorac Johnson |editor2=Gregory Peters |editor3=David Shoemaker | title = The Thoth [[Tarot]], [[Astrology]] & Other Selected Writings | year = 2010 | publisher = Teitan Press & College of Thelema of Northern California | isbn = 978-0-933429-27-7 }} *{{cite book | last = Seckler |editor1=Rorac Johnson |editor2=Gregory Peters |editor3=David Shoemaker | title = The [[Kabbalah]], [[Magick (Thelema)|Magick]], and [[Thelema]]. Selected Writings Volume II | year = 2012 | publisher = Teitan Press & College of Thelema of Northern California | isbn = 978-0-933429-28-4 }}
