[[File:Les Quatre Mousquetaires.jpg|thumb|right|[[Jacques Brugnon]] and [[Henri Cochet]] associated in double in 1930 (up), [[Jean Borotra]], « le Basque bondissant » (''the bounding Basque''), in 1931 (down-left), [[René Lacoste]] in 1929 (down-right).]]
'''The Four Musketeers''', ({{lang-fr|Les Quatre Mousquetaires}}) after a popular 1920s [[The Three Musketeers (1921 film)|film adaptation]] of [[Alexandre Dumas, père|Alexandre Dumas']] [[The Three Musketeers|classic]],<ref name="Bowers">Chris Bowers, [http://www.daviscup.com/en/news/articles/the-new-musketeers.aspx "The New Musketeers"], ''Davis Cup News'', February 27, 2009</ref> were [[French people|French]] [[tennis]] players who dominated the game in the second half of the 1920s and early 1930s, winning 20 [[Grand Slam in tennis|Grand Slam]] titles and 23 Grand Slam doubles.<ref name="Tandon">[http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/tennis/aus09/columns/story?columnist=tandon_kamakshi&id=3851105 "French foursome remains fearsome"], ''[[ESPN|ESPN.com]]'', January 22, 2009</ref>{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|pp=104–105|ps=}} They also led France to six straight [[Davis Cup]] wins, 1927–32, in an era when Cup matches enjoyed a prestige similar to today's [[FIFA World Cup]] finals. At its creation in 1927, the tournament that would later be known as [[French Open]]'s trophy was named the ''[[Coupe des Mousquetaires]]'' in honour of the quartet.<ref name="Bowers"/>

==The Musketeers==
The Musketeers were:
*[[Jean Borotra]] (1898–1994)<ref>{{cite news|author1=Christopher Clarey|title=Jean Borotra Is Dead at 95; One of Tennis's '4 Musketeers'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/18/obituaries/jean-borotra-is-dead-at-95-one-of-tennis-s-4-musketeers.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=18 July 1994}}</ref>{{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=45|ps=}}
*[[Jacques Brugnon]] (1895–1978){{sfnp|Grasso|2011|pp=50–51|ps=}}
*[[Henri Cochet]] (1901–1987){{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=66|ps=}}
*[[René Lacoste]] (1904–1996){{sfnp|Grasso|2011|p=167|ps=}}

While Brugnon was primarily a doubles specialist, Borotra, Cochet, and Lacoste won many singles titles. Between them, they won three [[US Open (tennis)|United States Championships]] at [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills]], six consecutive [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] titles from 1924 through 1929, and 10 titles in 11 years at the [[French Championships]], 1922 through 1932 (up to and including 1924, though, the tournament was only open to members of French tennis clubs, therefore wasn't a major tournament until 1925).{{sfnp|Wilson|2014|p=80–87|ps=}} From 1926 until 1930 a musketeer, Lacoste or Cochet, was ranked No. 1 in the world and in 1926 and 1927 all four musketeers were ranked in the top-10.<ref name=collins>{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Bud|authorlink=Bud Collins|title=The Bud Collins History of Tennis|year=2010|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=[New York]|isbn=978-0942257700|page=716|edition=2nd}}</ref>  The only player capable of challenging their dominance was the great American [[Bill Tilden]] ([[World number one male tennis player rankings|world number-one]] from 1920 until 1926, when Lacoste took over the position). The Musketeers were finally eclipsed by the arrival of [[Ellsworth Vines]], [[Fred Perry]] and [[Jack Crawford (tennis)|Jack Crawford]] on the international tennis scene in the first half of the 1930s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17029176 |title=French Tennis. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=2 December 1933  |page=15 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The success of The Four Musketeers in winning the [[1927 International Lawn Tennis Challenge|1927 Davis Cup]] against the United States was directly responsible for the decision by the [[French Tennis Federation]] to build the [[Stade Roland Garros|Roland Garros]] venue at Porte d'Auteuil.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roland-Garros – History of the Stadium|url=http://www.rolandgarros.com/en_FR/rg_year_round/201408271409194686687.html|website=www.rolandgarros.com|publisher=[[French Tennis Federation]] (FFT)}}</ref> The four men were national icons in France and all of them lived to be at least 83 years old, basking in glory for many years after their retirement from tennis. They were simultaneously inducted into the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] in Newport, Rhode Island, in 1976.

[[File:Les Quatre Nouveaux Mousquetaires.jpg|thumb|The ''New Musketeers'' (from top to bottom and left to right : [[Richard Gasquet|Gasquet]], [[Gilles Simon|Simon]], [[Gaël Monfils|Monfils]] and [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga|Tsonga]]) during the period 2008-2009.]]
The '''New Musketeers''',<ref name="Tandon"/> (''Nouveaux Mousquetaires'' or ''néo-Mousquetaires'') coined in ''[[L'Équipe]]'' and adopted by the [[List of newspapers in France|French press]], refers to the present-day squad of star players headlined by [[Gilles Simon]], [[Richard Gasquet]], [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]], and [[Gaël Monfils]].<ref>[https://www.lequipe.fr/Tennis/20081027_222443_les-copains-se-prennent-au-jeu_Dev.html "Les copains se prennent au jeu"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20110616145810/http://www.lequipe.fr/Tennis/20081027_222443_les-copains-se-prennent-au-jeu_Dev.html |date=2011-06-16 }}, ''L'Équipe'', October 28, 2008</ref> In 2008 France boasted four Top-20 players, a feat never before achieved since computer rankings were established in 1973.<ref name="Bowers"/> This configuration of the same four players in the Top-20 has been reproduced in mid-2011, in early 2012 and early 2016.

